<BR><h2><A NAME="files">
<IMG SRC="/pub/Graphics/Icons/doc1_icon.gif" WIDTH=40 HEIGHT=40 ALT=""></A>
Files in this Archive</h2>

<DL>
<DT><a href="acm_v_iit.alert"><B>acm_v_iit.alert</B></a>
<DD>Jan, 1995 article describing the confiscation of the
    Association for
    Computing Machinery computers by the Illinois Institute of technology. The
    confiscation occured because the student group had been allegedly hacking
    into another student groups computers and pulling pranks.
<DT><a href="cis_v_patterson.notes"><B>cis_v_patterson.notes</B></a>
<DD>Article by Richard Patterson stating that
    CompuServe claims that its members agree to be sued in CompuServe's 
    hometown of Columbus, Ohio by accepting membership of the service. 
    This statement was struck down in court on August 11, 1994 for lack of 
    personal jurisdiction and that internet connections were too tenuous 
    to sustain such jurisdiction.
<DT><a href="davis_case.docs"><B>davis_case.docs</B></a>
<DD>a list of files that have to deal with the Davis case and
    where to find them and how to get them by e-mail.
<DT><a href="davis_guilty_verdict.article"><B>davis_guilty_verdict.article</B></a>
<DD>May, 1994 article summarizing the Davis case
    where davis was convicted of distributing obscene materials on 
    computer disk.
<DT><a href="deatherage_case.note"><B>deatherage_case.note</B></a>
<DD>Note by Jon Pugh describing what he knew of Donald
    Deatherage who allegedly used his computer to prey on a 14-year old 
    boy with whom he met and commited various illegal acts.
<DT><a href="demberger_v_odtc_crypto_export.letters"><B>demberger_v_odtc_crypto_export.letters</B></a>
<DD>Letters between James Demberger
    and the Department of state regarding his creation and distribution of 
    an encryption program that the DOS believed violated ITAR.
<DT><a href="gottesman_lords_video_case.article"><B>gottesman_lords_video_case.article</B></a>
<DD>Article describing the controversy
    surrounding a California lower court's decision to hold a law 
    prohibiting the distribution of child pornography unconstitutional. 
    The question hinges on the statutes wording stating that a person must 
    'knowingly' transport or ship child pornography.
<DT><a href="lay_mci_phonecard_theft_case.note"><B>lay_mci_phonecard_theft_case.note</B></a>
<DD>Article dealing with the case where an MCI
    employee, Ivey Lay, allegedly stole more then 100,000 calling card numbers
    which were used to make over $50 million in calls.
<DT><a href="mcbride_demographics.disclaimer"><B>mcbride_demographics.disclaimer</B></a>
<DD>notice from JS McBride Co. announcing
    abandonment of McBride's plan to sell market demographic info gained my net
    monitoring (abandoned due to outcry from net users).
<DT><a href="mcintyre_v_ohio.decision"><B>mcintyre_v_ohio.decision</B></a>
<DD>Text of the McIntyre v. Ohio decision
<DT><a href="meeks_case.info"><B>meeks_case.info</B></a>
<DD>Article by Mark Voorhees regarding the protection that
    Brock Meeks would have in a defamation case regarding the internet 
    compared with protection given for the printed word.
<DT><a href="mike_diana_case.notes"><B>mike_diana_case.notes</B></a>
<DD>Notes and articles regarding the case of Mike
    Diana, the
    publisher of a zine, who was convicted of violating obscenity statutes with
    his drawn cartoons. He was sentenced to probation where he couldn't draw any
    obscene cartoons, even for personal use. Makes sense.
<DT><a href="naacp_tobacco_cases.notes"><B>naacp_tobacco_cases.notes</B></a>
<DD>Article about the NAACP case where the state
    attempted to compell the group to name its members in Alabama.
<DT><a href="ny_pen_register_appeal_93.decision"><B>ny_pen_register_appeal_93.decision</B></a>
<DD>Text of People v. Bialostok, a case
    involving wiretap and warrant law.
<DT><a href="nyt_v_sullivan_libel_pub_figures.notes"><B>nyt_v_sullivan_libel_pub_figures.notes</B></a>
<DD>Notes of case of New York Times v.
    Sullivan, a libel and defamation case
<DT><a href="pensacola_busts_effector.newsbyte"><B>pensacola_busts_effector.newsbyte</B></a>
<DD>Article regarding the bust of several BBS
    operators in Pensacola, FL for the distibution of obscene materials over
    computers.
<DT><a href="saban_perez_960603_legal_threat.letter"><B>saban_perez_960603_legal_threat.letter</B></a>
<DD>A person with a &quot;Mighty Morphin 
    Power Rangers&quot; fan page on the web gets legal threats from Saban 
    Entertainment, owner of the Power Ranger trademark. A perfect example of 
    clueless offline industry people who do not yet realize that such web 
    pages not only do not threaten them in any way, but actually provide 
    free advertising!
<DT><a href="shoars_v_epson_case.note"><B>shoars_v_epson_case.note</B></a>
<DD>Letter to the EFF asking about who won the Shoars
    v. Epson case (a case regarding whether a company could read a persons
    private e-mail)
<DT><a href="sjg_neidorf_eff.summary"><B>sjg_neidorf_eff.summary</B></a>
<DD>Legal summary of Steve Jackson Games case and
    United States v. Craig Neidorf.
<DT><a href="skwarla_tandy_bbs_case.info"><B>skwarla_tandy_bbs_case.info</B></a>
<DD>Article regarding the controversy of whether or
    not an employer has the right to fire someone for operating a BBS on
    their own equipment and on their own time.
<DT><a href="tbs_v_fcc_must-carry.decision"><B>tbs_v_fcc_must-carry.decision</B></a>
<DD>decision of Turner Broadcasting System v. FCC
    where cable companies were required to carry local comercial and public
    channels.
<DT><a href="trobee_v_aol_case.docs"><B>trobee_v_aol_case.docs</B></a>
<DD>Text of some of the pleadings of the Trobee v. AOL case
    where the plaintiff was fired allegedly fired without cause by the Defendant
    and allowed the electronic publishing of a slanderous article by another
    person on the service.
<DT><a href="us_v_microsoft_amici.brief"><B>us_v_microsoft_amici.brief</B></a>
<DD>Amici Brief of the United States v. Microsoft
    dealing with Microsoft's allegedly anticompetitive practices and its 
    monopoly with operating systems.
<DT><a href="west_v_doj.annouce"><B>west_v_doj.annouce</B></a>
<DD>Article reporting the DOJ investigation of West publishing
    for anti-trust violation.
</DL>

<br><hr><br>
<H2><A NAME="dirs">
<IMG SRC="/pub/Graphics/Icons/filefolder_icon.gif" WIDTH=40 HEIGHT=40
ALT=""></A> Subdirectories in This Archive</H2>

<DL>
<DT><A HREF=".."><B>Up to the Parent Directory</B><P></a>
<DT><a href="2600_mall_case/"><B>2600_mall_case/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information regarding the case where the Secret
    Service essentially raided a 2600 Magazine reader's club meeting 
    in a mall in 1992 and seized documents and other items. The readers are
    filing a lawsuit against the SS, who don't seem to've learned their lesson
    from the SJG case very well.
<DT><a href="AABBS_Thomases_Memphis/"><B>AABBS_Thomases_Memphis/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information regarding the bust of
    Amateur Action BBS sysops Robert and Carleen Thomas of California,
    prosecuted under Tennessee, and later Utah, law.
<DT><a href="Armstrong_v_President/"><B>Armstrong_v_President/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information dealing with the case 
    asking if agencies must deal with electronic records in the same 
    manner as they would paper records. This is linked to PROFS_case/.
<DT><a href="Avrahami_v_USNWR/"><B>Avrahami_v_USNWR/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info on Ram Avrahami's lawsuit against
    _US_News_and_World_Report_ for selling his name on a mailing list 
    without his permission. Though USNWP has won all the way to the appellate
    level, Avrahami is appealing to the Virginia Supreme Court. The case, 
    if it goes Avrahami's way, could have an immensely beneficial effect on 
    privacy, if widely influential in other jurisdictions, by finally 
    establishing an individual's proprietary interest in their own 
    personally identifiable information. The effect on the Internet would be 
    profound as well, and would resolve numerous privacy concerns such as 
    involuntary collection of personal information about web browsers by 
    the sites they visit, emailbox spamming, etc.
<DT><a href="BC_BBSes/"><B>BC_BBSes/</B></A>
<DD>directory of info related to the seizure of two British 
    Columbia, Canada, BBSs and the prosecution of their system operators.
<DT><a href="BITS-A-t-E_Spunk/"><B>BITS-A-t-E_Spunk/</B></A>
<DD>directory of info related to raids and possible eventual
    prosecution of Italian BBS BITS Against the Empire, and related police
    actions against &quot;online anarchists and terrorists&quot; associated with
    Spunk Press in the UK.
<DT><a href="Baker_UMich_case/"><B>Baker_UMich_case/</B></A>
<DD>directory of information on the Jake Baker censorship
    (or harassment/threats, depending on viewpoint) case, involving the U. of
    Michigan and the FBI).
<DT><a href="Bernstein_v_DoS/"><B>Bernstein_v_DoS/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information regarding the Bernstein v.
    Department of State. The case involves the exporting of strong
    encryption software.
<DT><a href="Cincinnati_BBSers_v_Hamilton_County/"><B>Cincinnati_BBSers_v_Hamilton_County/</B></A>
<DD>directory of info, including case 
    documents, from a massive lawsuit, pitting the users of a raided 
    Cincinnati Ohio bulletin board system (plaintiffs) against the local 
    sherrif and several other parts of the county government (defendants).
    Plaintiffs allege severe violations of their civil liberties. Attorneys
    for the plaintiffs, including Pete Kennedy of the SJG v. USSS case, 
    expect to win.
<DT><a href="Clue_v_InterNIC/"><B>Clue_v_InterNIC/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info on the Clue Computing v. NSI (InterNIC)
    lawsuit, in which Clue Computing is suing for a restraining order 
    blocking NSI from taking away Clue's domain name, at the behest of Hasbro,
    a company with a trademark on &quot;Clue&quot; in one particular category of 
    commerce.
<DT><a href="CPSR_v_FBI/"><B>CPSR_v_FBI/</B></A>
<DD>Direcotry of information regarding the case where the CPSR sued
    the FBI for information regarding their plan to expand wiretap power after
    the FBI failed to make the information public.
<DT><a href="CPSR_v_NSA/"><B>CPSR_v_NSA/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information regarding the case of the CPSR v. the NSA
    regarding the clipper chip technology.
<DT><a href="Canter_Siegel/"><B>Canter_Siegel/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information dealing with the legality of the
    Usenet &quot;spamming&quot; tactics of Canter and Siegel. No actual legal case
    related to this is currently underway. Symlinked to Greencard_spam/
<DT><a href="Clipper_FOIA/"><B>Clipper_FOIA/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information dealing with the Clipper key 
    technology and the and Gilmore's case against the NSA with the Freedom of
    Information Act. See also Gilmore_v_NSA.
<DT><a href="CoS_v_the_Net/"><B>CoS_v_the_Net/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information regarding the Church of
    Scientology v. the Net cases, including the Erlich v. CoS cases,
    CoS v. the Net case, FACTNet v. CoS.
<DT><a href="CRLP_v_DoJ/"><B>CRLP_v_DoJ/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info regarding Center for Reproductive Law &amp; 
    policy, et al., lawsuit against the Dept. of Justice, challenging the 
    constitutionality of the ban against online distribution of 
    abortion-related info, in the 1996 Telecommunications &quot;Reform&quot; Act. The 
    suit was filed Feb. 7, 1996.
<DT><a href="Cyber_Promotions_v_AOL/"><B>Cyber_Promotions_v_AOL/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info on lawsuit filed by Cyber 
    Promotions, a company specializing is &quot;spamming&quot; (bombarding Net 
    users' email boxes with advertisements), against America OnLine. AOL
    is alledged by CP to have taken all the CP &quot;spam&quot; emails that had not 
    been successfully delivered, altered the addresses on them, and sent them
    all to CP's two Internet access providers, who cut CP's service as a 
    result.
<DT><a href="DAETC_v_FCC/"><B>DAETC_v_FCC/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info on Denver Area Educational
    Telecommunications Consortium v. FCC, a Supreme Court case that, in June
    1996, ruled against what amounted to a cable tv censorship law.
<DT><a href="DCI_v_InterNIC/"><B>DCI_v_InterNIC/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info on the lawsuit filed by Data Concepts 
    Inc. against NSI (the domain registration half of the InterNIC), seeking
    to prevent NSI taking away Data Concepts' dci.com domain name at the 
    behest of Digital Consulting Inc., a company that has a trademark on &quot;DCI&quot;
    in one particular, narrow category of commerce.
<DT><a href="Dennis_Watson_case/"><B>Dennis_Watson_case/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info on the case of math professor Dennis 
    Watson, prosecuted for child pornography crimes, with much media 
    fanfare, after simply accessing certain newsgroups and verifying that 
    they did indeed contain such material, in the process of Watson's 
    work on school computing policies.
<DT><a href="DISC_v_InterNIC/"><B>DISC_v_InterNIC/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info regarding lawsuit filed by
    Dynamic Information Systems Corp. against Network Solutions Inc. (the 
    domain registration half of InterNIC), to prevent NSI from taking away 
    Dynamic's domain name at the best of DISC trademark holder Distributor 
    Information Systems Corp. (a.k.a. Distributor Information Services Corp.)
<DT><a href="Doe_v_SEPTA/"><B>Doe_v_SEPTA/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of documents from the John Doe v. SEPTA case in 
    the Federal Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit. Sets precedent on
    some medical privacy issues (reaffirms a constitutional interest, but 
    also rules that employers can have an interest in personally-identifiable
    medical information of employees, particularly if the employer 
    administers its own health care plans.)
<DT><a href="DoJ_v_Microsoft/"><B>DoJ_v_Microsoft/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information regarding the Department of Justice
    versus Microsoft and charges of anti-competitive practices.
<DT><a href="EFF_ACLU_v_DoJ/"><B>EFF_ACLU_v_DoJ/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info regarding EFF, ACLU, et al., and ALA, CDT, 
    CIEC, et al., lawsuits against the Dept. of Justice, challenging the 
    constitutionality of the Communications Decency Amendment to the 1996 
    Telecommunications &quot;Reform&quot; Act. The EFF/ACLU suit was filed Feb. 8, 
    1996, and the CIEC/CDT suit was filed Feb. 26, 1996. The cases were
    merged into one case for trial before a 3-judge panel in the Philadelphia
    US District Court. (This directory a.k.a. ALA_CDT_CIEC_v_DoJ/)
<DT><a href="EFGA_v_GA/"><B>EFGA_v_GA/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info about the EF-Georgia, EFF, ACLU, et al. v. 
    Governor &amp; Attorney General of Georgia case, challenging the 
    unconstitutional 1996 Georgia state legislature's &quot;Net police&quot; law. 
    ACLU is the lead plaintif in this case, funding the court costs and doing
    most of the legal work, though the impetus from the case, as well as
    the initial draft complain, comes from Electronic Frontiers Georgia 
    (EFGA).
<DT><a href="EPIC_v_FBI/"><B>EPIC_v_FBI/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information dealing with the case of EPIC v. the FBI
    with regards to wiretapping practices, and plans to make Clipper mandatory
    and/or outlaw non-&quot;escrowed&quot; encryption.
<DT><a href="FTC_v_Fortuna_Alliance/"><B>FTC_v_Fortuna_Alliance/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information on the Fortuna case: 
    Federal Trade Commission puts a stop (at least temporarily) to what
    Fortuna Alliance's apparent illegal pyramid scam
<DT><a href="FCC_v_Pacifica/"><B>FCC_v_Pacifica/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of documents relating to the 1974 George Carlin 
    &quot;Seven Dirty Words&quot; case, FCC v. Pacifica Foundation (the original
    Carlin monologue that was the subject of the case was actually called 
    &quot;Seven Words You Can Never Say on Television&quot;.) This case established
    indecency regulation in broadcasting, and for over two decades has 
    established the FCC as the largest censorship body in the world. This 
    case is essentially one of the forebears of the &quot;Communications Decency 
    Act&quot;.
<DT><a href="FBI_v_Tucholka_Tri_Tac_Games/"><B>FBI_v_Tucholka_Tri_Tac_Games/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information regarding the
    FBI raiding Tri Tac Games in order to try to find counterfeit govt. documents
<DT><a href="Foreign_and_local/"><B>Foreign_and_local/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information regarding cases in foreign and
    local/state jurisdictions
<DT><a href="Fred_Cherry_v_DoJ/"><B>Fred_Cherry_v_DoJ/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info on Fred Cherry's pro se lawsuit 
    challenging the Communications Decency Act.
<DT><a href="FTC_v_Fortuna_Alliance/"><B>FTC_v_Fortuna_Alliance/</B></A>
<DD>Link to a directory of info on Fortuna Alliance,
    a company that the FTC claims is defrauding Internet users via
    a pyramid scam.
<DT><a href="Giacalone_v_InterNIC/"><B>Giacalone_v_InterNIC/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info on Philip L. Giacalone's lawsuit
    against the InterNIC (specifically the Network Solutions Inc. half of 
    InterNIC), and TY, Inc., to prevent NSI from taking away Giacalone's 
    ty.com domain name (which NSI intended to do, at the behest of TY, 
    Inc., a company that has a trademark on &quot;TY&quot; in one particular category 
    of commerce.)
<DT><a href="Gilmore_v_NSA/"><B>Gilmore_v_NSA/</B></A>
<DD>directory of documents concerning John Gilmore's FOIA suits
    against the NSA. See also ITAR_FOIA/ and Clipper_FOIA/
<DT><a href="Homolka-WIRED_ban/"><B>Homolka-WIRED_ban/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of documents regarding the Canadian
    and British publications ban on information dealing with Karla Homolka.
<DT><a href="INSLAW/"><B>INSLAW/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information regarding the theft of POMIS by the
    DOJ, and the possible murder of a journalist during the coverup.
<DT><a href="Intel_v_Schwartz/"><B>Intel_v_Schwartz/</B></A>
<DD>Intel accused sysadmin Randal Schwartz of system 
    cracking. The facts don't seem to support this interpretation, but he
    was convicted under Oregon computer crime statutes for what some say
    was simply doing his job.
<DT><a href="ITAR_FOIA/"><B>ITAR_FOIA/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information regarding ITAR obtained via the 
    Freedom of Information Act. So far only FOIA requests have had to be 
    made, but it is likely that Gilmore &amp; Tien will have to file a lawsuit to
    get all of them.
<DT><a href="Junger_v_DoS/"><B>Junger_v_DoS/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info on PETER D. JUNGER v. DEPARTMENT OF 
    STATE, OFFICE OF DEFENSE TRADE CONTROLS, &amp; NATIONAL SECURITY AGENCY case.
    Junger claims the ITAR and AECA export restrictions on encryption 
    (particularly the absurdly broad definition of 'export', which includes
    &quot;disclosing&quot; to foreigners, unconstitutionally restricts Jungers First 
    Amendment rights to teach a class in which cryptography is detailed, if a 
    foreign student is present.
<DT><a href="Karn_Schneier_export/"><B>Karn_Schneier_export/</B></A>
<DD>directory of documents from the &quot;Applied
    Cryptography&quot; book + disk export case (book by Schneier, disk by Karn).
    The obtuseness of the Executive branch is truly stunning in this
    one.
<DT><a href="Kerberos_export/"><B>Kerberos_export/</B></A>
<DD>directory of docs from the Kerberos security
    program (stripped version) export case, put forward by
    Cygnus in an attempt to get export permission for
    this &quot;barebones&quot; version of Kerberos. This case
    revolves around &quot;technical data&quot; rather than
    &quot;cryptographic&quot; export restrictions.
<DT><a href="Knowledgenet_v_InterNIC_et_al/"><B>Knowledgenet_v_InterNIC_et_al/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info on the first lawsuit
    against the InterNIC over domain name intellectual property disputes.
    Knowledgenet Inc. in 1994 sued NSI (InterNIC) for issuing the 
    knowledgenet.com domain name, David L. Boone, for having the domain, and
    Boone's Internet access provider.
<DT><a href="LaMacchia/"><B>LaMacchia/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information regarding the LaMaccia case (alledged
    software piracy via BBS.)
<DT><a href="Liebling_v_Interlaw/"><B>Liebling_v_Interlaw/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info on Liebling v. Interlaw
    case. 'Lectric Law Library operator, Jeff Liebling, sued
    Interlaw Ltd. (interlaw.com) to protect LLL's similar interlaw.com
    address, which Interlaw Ltd. had told InterNIC to take away from LLL.
    The case was dismissed, the parties settled, and LLL has now 
    switched to using lectlaw.com.
<DT><a href="Lotus_cases/"><B>Lotus_cases/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info related to the Lotus Development Corp.
    v. Borland International, and Lotus Dev. Corp. v. Paperback Software 
    &quot;look-and-feel&quot; lawsuits (there are no civil liberties implications 
    in these cases, but vast implications for competition, open access 
    and free flow of information. If not overturned in the Supreme Court, 
    the Appellate Court's decision in Lotus v. Borland would allow 
    software giants to copyright not only graphical displays of menus, and 
    the code to generate them (quite appropriate under copyright law), but 
    also the underlying ideas or structure of the menuing systems in their 
    software - essentially a copyright on the methods of operation of a 
    computer program.
<DT><a href="Mitnick_WELL/"><B>Mitnick_WELL/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info related to the capture &amp; prosecution of
    Kevin Mitnick, who allegedly &quot;cracked&quot; the WELL and other Internet service
    providers
<DT><a href="Montreal_BBSes/"><B>Montreal_BBSes/</B></A>
<DD>directory of info on the seizure of several
    Montreal (Canada) BBSs and the prosecution of their operators.
<DT><a href="MTV_v_Curry/"><B>MTV_v_Curry/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info on the MTV v. Adam Curry domain name
    dispute. Music TeleVision sued former employee Adam Curry over his use
    of the mtv.com domain name, claiming trademark violation. Curry had
    registered mtv.com himself, while an MTV employee, after MTV declined to
    do so itself. After leaving the company, Curry put the domain name to
    non-MTV uses. MTV's case was fairly good - Curry was providing 
    entertainment-related info, and as such was arguably competing with MTV.
    Had Curry been doing anything else with the name, MTV's case would 
    probably have failed. MTV and Curry settled, and Curry now uses the 
    curry.com domain name, while MTV has taken over mtv.com. This case
    was arguably the first prominent domain name dispute, and opened the
    entire question of whether or not a domain name is intellectual property,
    and in what sense. In Curry's case, the answer leaned toward it
    being property in the trademark sense, just like a name on a product.
    Subsequent cases are pushing in the opposite direction, trying to
    establish domain names as property that benefits the holder (and ergo
    cannot be taken without cause and recompense).
<DT><a href="PGP_Zimmermann/"><B>PGP_Zimmermann/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information regarding the PGP
    and Phil Zimmerman investigation, including possible cases against
    ViaCrypt and Austin Codeworks. Symlinked to several other directory 
    names.
<DT><a href="Phiber_Optik/"><B>Phiber_Optik/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information regarding the indictment and
    prosecution of Mark Abene.
<DT><a href="Phrack_Neidorf_Riggs/"><B>Phrack_Neidorf_Riggs/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information regarding the case against
    Riggs and Neidorf of Phrack magazine for computer theft of the E911 
    system documents; part of &quot;Operation Sundevil&quot;. See also SJG/.
<DT><a href="Roadrunner_v_InterNIC/"><B>Roadrunner_v_InterNIC/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of info on Roadrunner v. NSI 
    (InterNIC), a case in which Roadrunner Computer Systems is seeking to 
    prevent Network Solutions Inc. (the domain registration half of InterNIC)
    from taking away its roadrunner.com domain name at the behest of 
    TIME/Warner Communications, who have a trademark on a particular 
    narrow use of the term &quot;Road Runner&quot;.
<DT><a href="RSA_v_NIST/"><B>RSA_v_NIST/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of documents regarding RSA and NIST and their 
    dispute over cryptography licensing.
<DT><a href="SJG/"><B>SJG/</B></A>
<DD>directory of documents pertaining to the Steve Jackson Games v. US
    Secret Service case, and several related &quot;Hacker Crackdown&quot; and
    &quot;Operation Sundevil&quot; cases, including the Legion of Doom/Jolnet, and
    Phrack/Neidorf/Riggs cases. (This directory is linked to several
    other names, including Operation_Sundevil.).
<DT><a href="Scientology_cases/"><B>Scientology_cases/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of information regarding the Church of
    Scientology's all-out attack against critics on the Net , including 
    the CoS v. Erlich Klemesrud &amp; Netcom, CoS v FACTnet Wollersheim &amp; 
    Penny, and CoS v. Lerma &amp; Washington Post cases. Symlinked to 
    numerous names (e.g. Erlich_v_CoS, Netcom_v_CoS, etc.)
<DT><a href="SPA_cases/"><B>SPA_cases/</B></A>
<DD>Directory of documents relating to the Software Publishers
    Association's Internet Anti-Piracy Campaign, the frivolous lawsuits filed
    as part of this campaign, and the associated, and deeply flawed, &quot;ISP 
    Code of Conduct&quot; being pushed by SPA and an alternative to getting sued.
<DT><a href="Stratton_Oakmont_Porush_v_Prodigy/"><B>Stratton_Oakmont_Porush_v_Prodigy/</B></A>
<DD>directory of documents regarding
    the Straton Oakmont Inc. &amp; Daniel Porush v. Prodigy Services Company
    case, in which Prodigy was held liable for users' postings, because
    Prodigy's censorship policy amounts to editorial control and therefore
    editorial responsibility.
<DT><a href="Toys_R_Us/"><B>Toys_R_Us/</B></A>
<DD>directory of documents relating to legal threats made by the 
    Toys &quot;R&quot; Us company against the author of the Roadkills-R-Us satirical 
    WWW pages.
<DT><a href="Wired_v_WWire/"><B>Wired_v_WWire/</B></A>
<DD>directory of info on the domain name dispute between
    Wired Magazine (wired.com) and Women's Wire (formerly wire.net, now 
    wwire.net, wwire.com, and womenswire.com amother others), an online 
    service. Wired Mag sent legal threats to WWire, claiming that the
    wire.net domain name infringed their trademark. The dispute was settled
    at least fairly amicably before any legal action ensued, with WWire
    acceding to the magazine's demands.
</DL>

<br><hr><br>
