<P></CENTER><BR><HR>
<BR><h2><A NAME="files">
<IMG SRC="/pub/Graphics/Icons/doc1_icon.gif" WIDTH=40 HEIGHT=40 ALT=""></A>
Files in this Archive</h2>

<DL>
<DT><a href="2600_mall_case_010596.update"><B>2600_mall_case_010596.update</B></a>
<DD>the federal appeals court in
    Washington, DC, has ordered the U.S. Secret Service to release
    information concerning the controversial &quot;hacker&quot; investigation,
    partially rejecting the agency's three-year attempt to withhold 
    documents concerning the 1992 &quot;Pentagon City Mall Raid.&quot;
<DT><a href="2600_mall_case.decision"><B>2600_mall_case.decision</B></a>
<DD>July 1994 decision by A federal judge in
    Washington, DC has ordered the release of Secret Service documents
    concerning the November 1992 raid on a meeting of 2600 Magazine
    readers at a shopping mall in Virginia. The documents were the subject
    of a Freedom of Information Act lawsuit filed by
    Computer Professionals for Social Responsibility
    (CPSR). The case is being litigated by the
    Electronic Privacy Information Center (EPIC).
    EFF and ACLU have also participated in various
    aspects of the case.
<DT><a href="2600_mall_case.eff"><B>2600_mall_case.eff</B></a>
<DD>a brief history and discussion about the case written
    Jan 22, 1993
<DT><a href="ss_appeal_epic.note"><B>ss_appeal_epic.note</B></a>
<DD>Notice (from EPIC) of the Secret Service's newly (5/95)
    filed appeal of the mall case FOIA decision (see
    2600_mall_case.decision, above).
</DL>

<br><hr><br>
