<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>EFF &quot;Censorship - Internet Censorship Legislation - Maryland&quot; Archive</TITLE><LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:webmaster@eff.org"></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF0000">

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=4 CELLPADDING=4 CELLSPACING=4>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER>
<TD><A HREF="http://www.eff.org/">EFFWeb Welcome Page</A></TD><H1></H1>
<TD><A HREF="http://www.eff.org/">Alerts</A></TD><H1></H1>
<TD><A HREF="http://www.eff.org/links.html#INDEXTOP">Archive Index</A></TD><H1></H1>
</TR></TABLE>

<h1><img src="/pub/Graphics/Icons/eff3d_white_icon.gif" ALT="">
<a name="top">EFF &quot;Censorship - Internet Censorship Legislation - Maryland&quot; Archive</a></h1>

<H5>http://www.eff.org/pub/Censorship/Internet_censorship_bills/Foreign_and_local/MD
</H5>



<h6>Last Updated Tue Jun 11 17:16:37 PDT 1996</h6><br>
<TABLE BORDER=4 CELLPADDING=4 CELLSPACING=4>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER>
<TD><A HREF="#files">Files</A></TD><H1></H1>
<TD><A HREF="#dirs">Subdirectories</A></TD><H1></H1>
<TD><A HREF="#onsite">On-Site Links</A></TD><H1></H1>
<TD><A HREF="#offsite">Off-Site Links</A></TD>
</TR></TABLE>


<P></CENTER><BR><HR>
<BR><h2><A NAME="files">
<IMG SRC="/pub/Graphics/Icons/doc1_icon.gif" ALT=""></A>
Files in this Archive</h2>

<DL>
<DT><a href="md_sb22_95.bill"><B>md_sb22_95.bill</B></a>
<DD>Maryland state senate bill 22: legislation to
    criminalize what is already a crime (distribution of child pornography via
    computer). Still pending as of our latest news, but may have passed 
    or died by now (June 1996). SB22 prohibits (redundantly) online child 
    porn, as well as sexual solicitation of a minor by computer.
    As with the Illinois bill, this appears to mean well, but, as usual,
    creates legal mayhem due to inconsistency with other statutes, and poses
    legal threats for innocent access providers. Also this bill, like a
    similar Kansas law, probably unconstitutionally redefines &quot;child porn&quot; to
    include even completely fake computer-generated art, as well as actual
    child porn and already-legally-obscene fake child porn of the hardcore 
    sort. Creates major sysop liability. Though high-minded, the law is very
    poorly thought out and dangerous for all system operators. If one of your
    users does something Maryland prosecutors don't like, you could go to
    prison for it.
<DT><a href="md_sb22_95_aclu.analysis"><B>md_sb22_95_aclu.analysis</B></a>
<DD>ACLU attacks SB22, an over-broad waste of
    time and effort that in the end holds system operators liable for the
    actions of users over whom they have no control.
</DL>

<br><hr><br>
